communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Incident Reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Last week, I submitted a request for records related to an incident on November 5th, where police responded to a report of an election judge striking another individual with a cane at a polling site. The locations associated with this incident are either 2700 N Sheffield Ave, Chicago, IL, 60614, or the intersection of W 63rd St & S Knox Ave, Chicago, IL, 60629. The original request sought the following: Incident Reports, 911 Audio, Dispatch Recordings, Body Cam Footage, and a CAD Log. However, the request was denied in full on the grounds of being overly broad in scope. I would like to emphasize that, under FOIA guidelines, if certain portions of a request are deemed too broad or are otherwise exempt, the department should not deny the request in full. Instead, the agency is obligated to produce any non-exempt records that are reasonably identifiable and within scope. Additionally, Incident Reports are a standard type of document routinely requested and disclosed by this agency. In fact, I have previously received such reports from the Chicago Police Department without the need for separate or narrowed requests. I respectfully request that this standard practice be applied to this case as well. 

To facilitate this process, I am submitting a revised, narrower request:

Incident Report: Any incident or police report(s) prepared in connection to a November 5th, where police responded to a report of an election judge striking another individual with a cane at a polling site. The locations associated with this incident are either 2700 N Sheffield Ave, Chicago, IL, 60614, or the intersection of W 63rd St & S Knox Ave, Chicago, IL, 60629.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Dhruv Mehrotra

communications.subject: Re: New submission from Records Request Form
communications.communication:
Dear Requester,
Thank you for reaching out. Wisconsin’s public records law requires that public records requests be reasonably specific as to subject matter. Wis. Stat. §19.35(1)(h). This is intended to prevent the records custodian from having to guess at what records a requester desires, and to avoid imposition of undue burdens on the university that would impair the functioning of the offices that need to be involved in processing a request. To the extent that the first part of your request, for “any and all records and materials...” constitutes a records request, it cannot be fulfilled because it does not identify a specific record or records in which you are interested in as required by Wis. Stat §19.35(1)(h).

If you could specify what you are looking for, we would be happy to move forward with your request once you've specified. To assist you further, below is what we have previously released related to this case to other requesters:

Incident report
Video and audio interviews with Khari Sandford and Alijah Larrue


Would this meet the needs of your request? If it does, we are happy to process this. If you would like other records, please specify what records you are requesting. If you would like access to the video and audio, please review, complete and return the attached form to us via email.

If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to reach back out.

Thank you,


Records | UW-Madison Police Department

1429 Monroe Street | Madison, WI 53711

O: (608) 262-4332  | records@uwpd.wisc.edu
